{{Chinese name|[[Deng (surname)|Teng]]}} {{Infobox Chinese-language singer and actor |name = A-fu |image = A-fu Teng 20150830 (cropped).jpg |caption = A-fu in 2015. |tradchinesename = 鄧福如 |simpchinesename = 邓福如 |pinyinchinesename = Dèng Fúrú |alma_mater = [[Shih Hsin University]] |birth_name = Teng Fu-ju |ancestry = |birth_date = {{birth date and age|1987|6|20|df=y}} |birth_place = [[Hsinchu]], [[Taiwan]] |death_date = |death_place = |restingplace = |restingplacecoordinates = |othername = A-fu Teng, Deng Furu |occupation = {{flatlist| *[[Singer]] *[[songwriter]] }} |genre = {{flatlist| *[[Mandopop]] *[[indie pop]] *[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] }} |instrument = Vocals |voicetype = |label = Forward Music |yearsactive = 2007–present |currentmembers = |pastmembers = |associatedact = Lazy Bomb |spouse = |partner = |children = |parents = |influences = |influenced = |website = |goldenmelodyawards = |ntsawards = |awards = }}
'''Teng Fu-ju''' ({{zh|t=鄧福如|s=邓福如|p=Dèng Fúrú|first=t}}; born 20 June 1987), known by her [[stage name]] '''A-fu''' ({{zh|c=阿福|p=Ā fú}}), is a [[Taiwanese people|Taiwanese]] singer and songwriter. Prior to her solo debut in the music scene, A-fu was a member of Lazy Bomb, an indie band, and a [[Demo (music)|demo]] singer. She is known for her [[cover version]] of "[[Nothin' on You]]" by [[B.o.B]] and [[Bruno Mars]], which drew wide attention on [[YouTube]] in 2010. In May 2011, A-fu released her debut studio album, ''That's How It Is'', for which she received a nomination for Best New Artist at the [[23rd Golden Melody Awards]].<ref name="goldenmelody"/>
==Early life== Born in [[Hsinchu City]] on 20 June 1987, A-fu grew up in the countryside in [[Xiangshan District, Hsinchu|Xiangshan District]] and in [[Changhua County]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://udn.com/NEWS/ENTERTAINMENT/ENT6/7966023.shtml |title=菲船事件衝擊 阿福MV郵輪夢碎 |work=UDN |date=16 June 2013 |accessdate=22 December 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130619002332/http://udn.com/NEWS/ENTERTAINMENT/ENT6/7966023.shtml |archivedate=19 June 2013 }}</ref> Both her parents run a rental car business together, and as they were often busy with work when she was young, A-fu and her elder sister, Hsing Ju, spent much of their childhood under the care of their aunt.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.chinatimes.com/newspapers/20130730000847-260112 | title=阿福發夢穿越古羅馬 談情賞夜景 | work=China Times | date=30 July 2013}}</ref> Despite this, A-fu still maintains a close relationship with her mother and grew up influenced by her mother's love for music, in particular songs by [[Teresa Teng]]. At a young age, A-fu entered in singing and recitation competitions. Also, at her mother's request, she learned the standard Mandarin enunciation by watching the Taiwanese educational programme ''The Daily Characters'' (每日一字) hosted by news presenter Lee Yen-chiu, which perhaps, has shaped her distinctive vocals, in a way.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://blog.udn.com/hurt633/5230339 | title=美聲素人「阿福」- 征服9億人 | work=UDN | accessdate=22 December 2015}}</ref>
She attended Kuang-Fu High School, a [[comprehensive high school]] in Hsinchu, and graduated from [[Shih Hsin University]] with a degree in public relations and advertising in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.shu.edu.tw/web/dp/a_pc/shut01_pc5.html |title=公共關係暨廣告學系 - 知名校友 |work=SHU |accessdate=22 December 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151223044116/http://m.shu.edu.tw/web/dp/a_pc/shut01_pc5.html |archivedate=23 December 2015 }}</ref>
==Career== [[File:Afu teng 2013aug31 resized.jpg|thumb|A-fu in 2013.]]
During her college years, A-fu was the lead singer of an indie band called Lazy Bomb. The band released a self-titled [[Extended play|EP]] in November 2007 and disbanded shortly after.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.5music.com.tw/CDList-C.asp?cdno=428475678514 | title=首張同名EP | work=5music | accessdate=22 December 2015}}</ref> Around this time, A-fu met music producer AL (何官錠), who is also a member and keyboard player of the pop rock band Six Plus (六甲樂團).<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nownews.com/n/2010/10/12/633978 | title=神祕女「聲」爆紅！四十萬網友問何方神聖？ | work=NOWnews | accessdate=22 December 2015}}</ref> She started collaborating with AL as a [[Demo (music)|demo]] singer. The first demo which she recorded, titled "Sheng Sheng Man" (聲聲慢), was chosen as the ending theme song for the first season of the Chinese TV series ''[[Justice Bao (2010 TV series)|Justice Bao]]''. The ''Zhong guo feng'' music style of the song, coupled with A-fu's crystal-clear voice and diction, generated considerable buzz among the Chinese netizens. Soon after, A-fu's singing caught the attention of veteran host [[Chang Hsiao-yen]], who later signed A-fu to her record label Forward Music. While awaiting the release of her debut album, A-fu garnered media attention after uploading her first video on [[YouTube]] in September 2010, her [[cover version]] of [[B.o.B]] and [[Bruno Mars]]'s "[[Nothin' on You]]", which had racked up more than a million views within a week. She followed with more covers of popular hits, which includes "[[Bizarre Love Triangle]]", "Qing Hua Ci" (青花瓷) by [[Jay Chou]], [[Bruno Mars]]'s "[[Just the Way You Are (Bruno Mars song)|Just the Way You Are]]" and so forth. In December 2010, A-fu was featured as a [[backup singer]] during Stella Chang's comeback concert in Taiwan.<ref name="2011搜尋人氣大獎／最受歡迎新人歌手─鄧福如">{{cite web | url=https://tw.celebrity.yahoo.com/news/2011%E6%90%9C%E5%B0%8B%E4%BA%BA%E6%B0%A3%E5%A4%A7%E7%8D%8E-%E6%9C%80%E5%8F%97%E6%AD%A1%E8%BF%8E%E6%96%B0%E4%BA%BA%E6%AD%8C%E6%89%8B-%E9%84%A7%E7%A6%8F%E5%A6%82-035402599.html | title=2011搜尋人氣大獎／最受歡迎新人歌手─鄧福如 | work=Yahoo! | accessdate=22 December 2015}}</ref>
A-fu's debut album, ''That's How It Is'', was released on 27 May 2011 and features a studio version of "Sheng Sheng Man" and her cover of "Nothin' on You".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.5music.com.tw/CDList-C.asp?cdno=432425679095 | title=原來如此!! | work=5music | accessdate=22 December 2015}}</ref> The album sold more than 25,000 copies in Taiwan within a month of its release.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://tw.news.yahoo.com/%E5%BC%B5%E5%B0%8F%E7%87%95%E4%B8%8D%E8%B2%B7%E6%A6%9C-%E9%98%BF%E7%A6%8F%E8%B3%A3%E5%94%B1%E9%9D%A0%E8%87%AA%E5%B7%B1-190636428.html | title=張小燕不買榜 阿福賣唱靠自己 | work=Yahoo! | accessdate=22 December 2015}}</ref> To further promote the album, A-fu performed a sold-out show at the Riverside Live House in Taipei on 25 June 2011, with [[Van Fan]] appearing as guest performer.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.riverside.com.tw/index.php?option=com_livehouse&show_time=2011-06 | title=A-Fu 鄧福如【原來如此】樂福音樂會 | work=Riverside | accessdate=22 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://ent.163.com/11/0627/08/77HU4AAD00031H2L.html | title=阿福首次开唱歌迷爆满 与范逸臣对唱情歌 | work=NetEase | accessdate=22 December 2015}}</ref> On 3 July 2011, A-fu made a guest appearance at [[Jam Hsiao]]'s mini-concert at [[Tamsui Fisherman's Wharf]], performing "Just the Way You Are" and "Wei Tian Ci" (未填詞).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tw.twent.chinayes.com/Content/20110703/kdxxmth5pgg7o.shtml |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316113132/http://tw.twent.chinayes.com/Content/20110703/kdxxmth5pgg7o.shtml |dead-url=yes |archive-date=16 March 2014 |title=阿福助陣蕭敬騰開心跳針 下次想挑戰主持(組圖) |work=Yes娛樂 |accessdate=22 December 2015 }}</ref> In 2012, A-fu was nominated for Best New Artist at the 23rd Golden Melody Awards but lost to [[Ilid Kaolo]].<ref name="goldenmelody"/>
Her next release, an [[extended play]] titled ''Happiness Is Around Us'', was released on 7 March 2012. The second single off of the album, "Where Is The Love?", a self-composed track, was featured as an insert song in the drama series ''[[Big Red Riding Hood]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.5music.com.tw/CDList-C.asp?cdno=433395678978 | title=你好,哈波尼斯EP | work=5music | accessdate=22 December 2015}}</ref>
On 7 June 2013, A-fu released her second studio album, ''Sky Island'', which debuted at number one on the Five Music Mandarin Album sales chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.5music.com.tw/CDTop.asp |title=5大金榜 - 第24 週 統計時間：2013/6/7 - 2013/6/13 |work=5music |accessdate=22 December 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130925131747/http://www.5music.com.tw/cdtop.asp |archivedate=25 September 2013 }}</ref> It includes the track "Rang Wo Ai Shang Wo" (讓我愛上我) from the [[soundtrack album]] for the film ''Step Back to Glory'' (志氣).<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.5music.com.tw/CDList-C.asp?cdno=434425679084 | title=天空島(正式版) | work=5music | accessdate=22 December 2015}}</ref> In May of that year, A-fu performed "[[Tie a Yellow Ribbon Round the Old Oak Tree]]" at [[Teresa Teng]]'s memorial concert at [[Taipei Arena]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cna.com.tw/News/FirstNews/201305120041-1.aspx | title=紀念鄧麗君 鍾鎮濤領巨星獻聲 | work=CNA | accessdate=22 December 2015}}</ref>
Her third studio album, ''Own Categories'', was released on 19 June 2015. It features a duet, "Stop At The Crossing Ahead" (前面路口停), with [[Xiao Yu (singer)|Xiao Yu]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/hot-tracks-1 | title=Hot tracks | work=The Straits Times | accessdate=22 December 2015}}</ref>
== Personal life == In January 2016, it was revealed that A-fu and blogger How How are in a relationship.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://star.ettoday.net/news/625751 | title=鄧福如牽手網紅How How 男友「KUSO影片」證熱戀！ | work=ETtoday | accessdate=23 March 2017}}</ref>
