{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2012}} {{Use British English|date=August 2012}} {{Infobox chess player |name = Jacob Aagaard |image = Jacob Aagaard.jpg |caption = Jacob Aagaard, 2008 |birthname = Jacob Aagaard |country = [[Scotland]] |birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1973|7|31|df=y}} |birth_place = [[Denmark]] |death_date = |death_place = |title = [[Grandmaster (chess)|Grandmaster]] (2007) |peakrating = 2538 (July 2009) |FideID = 1401815 }}
'''Jacob Aagaard''' (born 31 July 1973) is a [[Denmark|Danish]]-born [[Scotland|Scottish]] [[chess]] [[Grandmaster (chess)|grandmaster]] and the 2007 [[British Chess Championship|British Chess Champion]]. He is Scotland's third highest rated player as of February 2018, with an [[Elo rating]] of 2481. In 2004, he took second place in the [[Scottish Chess Championship]]. In 2005, he took first place in the Scottish Championship but was not a British citizen, so the title went to [[Craig Pritchett]]. In 2012 he won the title, the first time he played and was eligible to win it. He is also a chess author and co-owner of [[Quality Chess]], a chess publishing house.<ref>{{cite web|author=Speelman, Jon|title=Speelman on Chess|url=http://sport.guardian.co.uk/chess/story/0,,2151704,00.html|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|date=19 August 2007|accessdate=2008-03-07|authorlink=Jon Speelman}}</ref>
In 2011, Aagaard was awarded the title of FIDE Senior Trainer.
In 2012, Jacob won the Scottish Chess Championships with a score of 7/9
Aagaard is the only chess writer in the world to win all four major Book of the Year awards: English Chess Federation (2010), ChessCafe.com (2001), Association of Chess Professionals (2013) and the Boleslavsky Medal from FIDE's trainer committee (2012).
